When I was an investment banker, one thing that I did was pitch convertible=
 bond offerings to companies. A coverage banker =E2=80=94=C2=A0an investmen=
t banker whose job was to know companies and advise them on financial topic=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0would bring me to a meeting with the chief financial offic=
er of one of her companies to talk about convertible bonds.=C2=A0And I woul=
d come in and=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cthe convertible bond market is hot, you sho=
uld do one, we think you could raise $200 million of 5-year convertibles an=
d pay 2% interest with a 30% conversion premium.=E2=80=9D Most of the time,=
 their eyes would glaze over and they=E2=80=99d nod politely and say =E2=80=
=9Cthanks for that, very interesting=E2=80=9D and move on with their day an=
d not do a convertible. But sometimes they would say =E2=80=9Coh yes we do =
need $200 million and those terms sound attractive, let=E2=80=99s do it nex=
t week,=E2=80=9D and then we=E2=80=99d do some business and earn some fees.=
 And that is life as a product banker.
I was not, in those conversations, making a firm bid for those convertible =
bonds. That is mostly not how it works.
  [1]
 The company was not going to sell those bonds to me; it was going to sell =
them to the market, to convertible arbitrage hedge funds and other investor=
s who buy convertibles. (We would advise the company and market and underwr=
ite the bonds.) The terms the company would get =E2=80=94=C2=A0the size and=
 interest rate and conversion premium =E2=80=94=C2=A0would depend on what t=
hose investors were willing to take. I made no promises. I just had a page =
in a pitchbook with an estimate of what the market might want.
That estimate was cooked up back at the office the day before,=C2=A0using a=
 convertible bond pricing model and somewhere between =E2=80=A6=C2=A0let=E2=
=80=99s say two and 45 minutes of banker time? Sometimes we would pitch an =
important client who might really want to do a convertible, and so there=E2=
=80=99d be some discussion about market appetite and the company=E2=80=99s =
credit and its financing needs and the parameters to use in the pricing mod=
el; senior people would get involved to give their informed view of what th=
e market might think, and we=E2=80=99d reach a consensus on aggressive-but-=
achievable terms to show the client. Other times I=E2=80=99d be flying to s=
ee five random companies in an afternoon, small companies with no credit ra=
tings who had never done a convertible and never would. Then an analyst wou=
ld chuck some guesses into the model, get some numbers out, and type them i=
nto a pitch book. Sometimes those guesses would be wrong. This did not matt=
er, though, because the client=E2=80=99s eyes would glaze over and they=E2=
=80=99d throw the pitch book in the garbage and that would be that.
But every once in a long while one of=C2=A0those=C2=A0pitches would work, a=
nd the client would say =E2=80=9Cyes let=E2=80=99s do it next week,=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0and then we=E2=80=99d all sit down and be like =E2=80=9Cwait can t=
his company actually do the thing we pitched?=E2=80=9D There is the possibi=
lity of adverse selection here: If you pitch very attractive terms to a com=
pany that could not actually get those terms (because your analyst priced i=
t up in two minutes assuming it was a good credit, but actually it was a ba=
d credit), then the company is more likely to say =E2=80=9Cthat sounds grea=
t I want that,=E2=80=9D and then you are on the hook to do the deal.
Of course we were not=C2=A0really=C2=A0on the hook. We could go back to the=
 company and say =E2=80=9Chey, I know that in my pitch book I said you coul=
d raise a $200 million convertible with a 2% interest rate and a 30% conver=
sion premium, but we actually gave that no thought at all, and now we have =
given it some thought and the correct numbers are $100 million, 4% and 20%.=
=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s totally allowed! We were not held to the terms we =
pitched; we had no binding contract with the company to deliver it those te=
rms. But if we did that:
=09The company=E2=80=99s CFO would give us a disappointed look, and=09The c=
overage investment banker would give us a disappointed look, because we mad=
e=C2=A0her=C2=A0look bad in front of the client.

Also the company might change its mind about doing a convertible (quite rea=
sonably!) and we wouldn=E2=80=99t get a fee, and the coverage banker might =
stop bringing me to pitch meetings (quite reasonably!) and I would miss out=
 on future business. But realistically the biggest and most immediate probl=
em was the disappointed looks. This would mostly happen over phone calls, s=
o you had to imagine the disappointed looks, but that was not hard to do.
I can=E2=80=99t really tell you what the answer is here; =E2=80=9Chope the =
company changes its mind,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chope market conditions get=
 better so you can do the deal you pitched=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chope marke=
t conditions get worse so=C2=A0you have an excuse for doing a worse deal=E2=
=80=9D are the main=C2=A0possibilities. One way to be=C2=A0good at this sor=
t of banking would be to get everything right, so that every pitch contains=
 realistic terms, but that probably takes more time and effort than it=E2=
=80=99s worth. The =E2=80=94=C2=A0harder? =E2=80=94=C2=A0way to be good at =
this sort of banking is to be a person who can get on a call with a client =
and say =E2=80=9Cthat good thing we promised you, we can=E2=80=99t do it, b=
ut we can do this other worse thing,=E2=80=9D and have the client walk away=
 feeling good about it. That is charm, or whatever it is.
Anyway all of this is hypothetical and I never got anything wrong, but imag=
ine if I did.
Separately here is a US Securities and Exchange Commission enforcement acti=
on from last week=C2=A0against S&P Global Ratings:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged S&P Global Ratings, a =
nationally recognized statistical rating organization (NRSRO) registered wi=
th the Commission, with violating conflict of interest rules designed to pr=
event sales and marketing considerations from influencing credit ratings.
The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that an issuer engaged S&P to rate a jumbo re=
sidential mortgage backed security transaction in July 2017. Over a five-da=
y period in August 2017, S&P commercial employees=E2=80=94employees respons=
