      Carbon accounting
   =20
 =20

Let us say, for simplicity, that you run a company that uses electric power=
, and you get half of your power from wind=C2=A0and half of your power from=
 coal. The coal power you use puts one ton of carbon dioxide into the atmos=
phere per year. The wind power you use puts zero tons of carbon dioxide int=
o the atmosphere;=C2=A0it is completely clean. The question is: How much to=
tal carbon emissions are you responsible for?
You might say: Well, one ton of carbon from the coal, plus zero tons from t=
he wind, equals one ton. But we   talked the other day about the financial =
services specialty of ESG Consultant But Evil, where you advise companies o=
n how to reduce their =E2=80=9Ccarbon emissions=E2=80=9D (a matter of accou=
nting convention)=C2=A0without actually reducing their carbon emissions=C2=
=A0(a matter of actual physical emissions into the atmosphere). And=C2=A0as=
 an accounting convention, you can improve on this math. Here is some bette=
r math:
=09Your coal power adds one ton of carbon to the atmosphere.=09Your wind po=
wer=C2=A0subtracts=C2=A0one ton of carbon from the atmosphere, because if y=
ou weren=E2=80=99t using the wind power you=E2=80=99d be using coal, which =
would add one ton of carbon emissions, and you=E2=80=99re not doing that. S=
o you can count the ton of carbon that you=E2=80=99re=C2=A0not=C2=A0using a=
s a=C2=A0reduction=C2=A0of emissions.=09So your net carbon emissions are ze=
ro.

I swear this is a real thing, or almost. Here=E2=80=99s a Bloomberg article=
 titled =E2=80=9CJunk Carbon Offsets Are What Make These Big Companies =E2=
=80=98Carbon Neutral=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D:

Airlines, online retailers, industrial firms and energy producers now rely =
heavily on the cheapest and most suspect type of offset =E2=80=94 those tie=
d to renewable-energy projects.=C2=A0
Most of these renewable-energy offset purchases are not credible, according=
 to Julio Friedmann, chief scientist at consultancy Carbon Direct and one o=
f six researchers who reviewed the data. =E2=80=9CI would consider these to=
 be low-quality credits that did not avoid or reduce greenhouse-gas emissio=
ns,=E2=80=9D he said.
Purchasing credits tied to support of solar or wind projects sounds good fo=
r the climate. But experts consider these offsets largely bogus. The issue =
is timing: many renewable offsets came into being just as solar and wind po=
wer established themselves as the cheapest source of energy in most countri=
es. Selling offsets for small sums as a way to support the economics of ren=
ewables doesn=E2=80=99t provide any real benefit if it=E2=80=99s already ch=
eaper than building new coal or gas power plants.
That=E2=80=99s the basis on which these offsets are generated: additional s=
upport for something clean is assumed to displace a dirtier alternative. Of=
fsets built on firmer footing =E2=80=94 and costing far more money =E2=80=
=94 now exist from a nascent industry that directly removes carbon dioxide =
from the air.=C2=A0

The idea is that if you support a renewable project =E2=80=94=C2=A0for inst=
ance by committing in advance to pay for some power produced by a proposed =
renewable project, so that it can get financing to get built =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then you are reducing emissions and should be rewarded. But that can end=
 up looking a lot like double-counting, where your use of renewables doesn=
=E2=80=99t add to your emissions but also, somehow, subtracts from them.

