  [1] Sometimes it works that way =E2=80=94 a =E2=80=9Cbought deal,=E2=80=
=9D where the bank buys securities at a price and takes the market risk its=
elf =E2=80=94 but that=E2=80=99s not how run-of-the-mill convertible pitche=
s work.


  [2] We talked about this theory   last week; I summarized it by saying =
=E2=80=9CCustomers could make levered bets on cryptocurrencies on FTX and b=
e automatically liquidated if the bets moved against them, and this liquida=
tion seems to have consisted largely of Alameda buying their positions. Thi=
s was a good experience for customers =E2=80=94 it made betting on FTX more=
 predictable and less risky =E2=80=94 and possibly good for Alameda, if it =
bought stuff that went down and then the stuff went up again. But when the =
Luna token collapsed earlier this year, Alameda would (on this theory) have=
 been buying tons of Luna all the way down, leaving it with a huge stash of=
 worthless Luna and a big loss.=E2=80=9D This  Twitter thread fleshes out t=
hat speculation a bit.


