10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note: </strong><em>Money S=
tuff will be off for the rest of the week. Happy Thanksgiving!</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">S&amp;P</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I was an investment banker, one thing tha=
t I did was pitch convertible bond offerings to companies. A coverage banke=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0an investment banker whose job was to know companies and a=
dvise them on financial topics =E2=80=94=C2=A0would bring me to a meeting w=
ith the chief financial officer of one of her companies to talk about conve=
rtible bonds.=C2=A0And I would come in and=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cthe convertibl=
e bond market is hot, you should do one, we think you could raise $200 mill=
ion of 5-year convertibles and pay 2% interest with a 30% conversion premiu=
m.=E2=80=9D Most of the time, their eyes would glaze over and they=E2=80=99=
d nod politely and say =E2=80=9Cthanks for that, very interesting=E2=80=9D =
and move on with their day and not do a convertible. But sometimes they wou=
ld say =E2=80=9Coh yes we do need $200 million and those terms sound attrac=
tive, let=E2=80=99s do it next week,=E2=80=9D and then we=E2=80=99d do some=
 business and earn some fees. And that is life as a product banker.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I was not, in those conversations, making a fi=
rm bid for those convertible bonds. That is mostly not how it works.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> The company was not going to sell those bonds to me; it was going to s=
ell them to the market, to convertible arbitrage hedge funds and other inve=
stors who buy convertibles. (We would advise the company and market and und=
erwrite the bonds.) The terms the company would get =E2=80=94=C2=A0the size=
 and interest rate and conversion premium =E2=80=94=C2=A0would depend on wh=
at those investors were willing to take. I made no promises. I just had a p=
age in a pitchbook with an estimate of what the market might want.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That estimate was cooked up back at the office=
 the day before,=C2=A0using a convertible bond pricing model and somewhere =
between =E2=80=A6=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s say two and 45 minutes of banker time?=
 Sometimes we would pitch an important client who might really want to do a=
 convertible, and so there=E2=80=99d be some discussion about market appeti=
te and the company=E2=80=99s credit and its financing needs and the paramet=
ers to use in the pricing model; senior people would get involved to give t=
heir informed view of what the market might think, and we=E2=80=99d reach a=
 consensus on aggressive-but-achievable terms to show the client. Other tim=
es I=E2=80=99d be flying to see five random companies in an afternoon, smal=
l companies with no credit ratings who had never done a convertible and nev=
er would. Then an analyst would chuck some guesses into the model, get some=
 numbers out, and type them into a pitch book. Sometimes those guesses woul=
d be wrong. This did not matter, though, because the client=E2=80=99s eyes =
would glaze over and they=E2=80=99d throw the pitch book in the garbage and=
 that would be that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But every once in a long while one of=C2=A0tho=
se<em>=C2=A0</em>pitches would work, and the client would say =E2=80=9Cyes =
let=E2=80=99s do it next week,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and then we=E2=80=99d all sit =
down and be like =E2=80=9Cwait can this company actually do the thing we pi=
tched?=E2=80=9D There is the possibility of adverse selection here: If you =
pitch very attractive terms to a company that could not actually get those =
terms (because your analyst priced it up in two minutes assuming it was a g=
ood credit, but actually it was a bad credit), then the company is more lik=
ely to say =E2=80=9Cthat sounds great I want that,=E2=80=9D and then you ar=
e on the hook to do the deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course we were not=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</e=
m>on the hook. We could go back to the company and say =E2=80=9Chey, I know=
 that in my pitch book I said you could raise a $200 million convertible wi=
th a 2% interest rate and a 30% conversion premium, but we actually gave th=
at no thought at all, and now we have given it some thought and the correct=
 numbers are $100 million, 4% and 20%.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s totally allo=
wed! We were not held to the terms we pitched; we had no binding contract w=
ith the company to deliver it those terms. But if we did that:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company=E2=80=99s CFO would give u=
s a disappointed look, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The cov=
erage investment banker would give us a disappointed look, because we made=
=C2=A0<em>her=C2=A0</em>look bad in front of the client.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also the company might change its mind about d=
oing a convertible (quite reasonably!) and we wouldn=E2=80=99t get a fee, a=
nd the coverage banker might stop bringing me to pitch meetings (quite reas=
onably!) and I would miss out on future business. But realistically the big=
gest and most immediate problem was the disappointed looks. This would most=
ly happen over phone calls, so you had to imagine the disappointed looks, b=
ut that was not hard to do.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can=E2=80=99t really tell you what the answe=
r is here; =E2=80=9Chope the company changes its mind,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Chope market conditions get better so you can do the deal you pitched=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chope market conditions get worse so=C2=A0you have an ex=
cuse for doing a worse deal=E2=80=9D are the main=C2=A0possibilities. One w=
ay to be=C2=A0good at this sort of banking would be to get everything right=
, so that every pitch contains realistic terms, but that probably takes mor=
e time and effort than it=E2=80=99s worth. The =E2=80=94=C2=A0harder? =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0way to be good at this sort of banking is to be a person who ca=
n get on a call with a client and say =E2=80=9Cthat good thing we promised =
you, we can=E2=80=99t do it, but we can do this other worse thing,=E2=80=9D=
 and have the client walk away feeling good about it. That is charm, or wha=
tever it is.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway all of this is hypothetical and I never=
 got anything wrong, but imagine if I did.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Separately here is a <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29776711.281548/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0yMDU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB364383cd" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">US Securities and Exchange Commission enforcement action from last wee=
k</a>=C2=A0against S&amp;P Global Ratings:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today c=
harged S&amp;P Global Ratings, a nationally recognized statistical rating o=
rganization (NRSRO) registered with the Commission, with violating conflict=
 of interest rules designed to prevent sales and marketing considerations f=
rom influencing credit ratings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that an issuer e=
ngaged S&amp;P to rate a jumbo residential mortgage backed security transac=
tion in July 2017. Over a five-day period in August 2017, S&amp;P commercia=
l employees=E2=80=94employees responsible for managing the relationship wit=
h the issuer=E2=80=94on several occasions attempted to pressure the S&amp;P=
 analytical employees=E2=80=94employees responsible for evaluating and assi=
gning the rating=E2=80=94to rate the transaction consistent with preliminar=
y feedback the analytical employees had given the customer that turned out =
to include a calculation error. Despite sending the communications through =
the compliance department as required by S&amp;P=E2=80=99s policies and pro=
cedures at that time, some emails sent by the S&amp;P commercial employees =
to the S&amp;P analytical team contained statements reflecting sales and ma=
rketing considerations. The order finds that, as a result of the content, u=
rgent nature, high volume, and compressed timing of the communications, the=
 S&amp;P commercial employees became participants in the rating process dur=
ing a time when they were influenced by sales and marketing considerations.=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S&amp;P initially told the customer=C2=A0that =
it would probably get a good rating. Then it discovered that it had made a =
calculation error, and the rating would be worse than it had =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0not promised, but given =E2=80=9Cpreliminary feedback=E2=80=9D about any=
way. The customer was, understandably, annoyed, <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29776711.281548/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9sa=
XRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjIvMzQtOTYzMDgucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5e234=
57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">and called the</a> =E2=80=9CS&amp;P commercial employees=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0the coverage salespeople =E2=80=94=C2=A0to yell at them.=
 =E2=80=9CThe S&amp;P commercial employees stated to other commercial team =
members, at that time, that the issuer had threatened that, if S&amp;P=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=98ratings were changing, [S&amp;P was] off the deal=E2=80=99=
 and that, =E2=80=98by removing [S&amp;P] from the deal, [the issuer] was a=
lso ending the relationship in RMBS indefinitely and would also drop all [S=
&amp;P] servicer and originator rankings.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D The commercial =
employees, uh, conveyed this displeasure to the analytical team. The analyt=
ical team was chagrined, and=C2=A0=E2=80=9CS&amp;P analytical employees, wo=
rking late on the night before the preliminary rating committee meeting,=E2=
=80=9D maybe bent the requirements a bit to get to the client-friendly resu=
lt they had previously promised.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yes, look, if you make a mistake in your m=
odel, and as a result of that mistake you tell an issuer that you=E2=80=99l=
l probably rate their bonds AAA, and then they hire you to rate the bonds, =
and you catch the mistake and realize that you can only rate the bonds AA, =
and the issuer gives you a disappointed look, and the relationship person g=
ives you a disappointed look, and the issuer says things like =E2=80=9Cwell=
 I won=E2=80=99t be doing business with you anymore,=E2=80=9D you=C2=A0<em>=
could=C2=A0</em>just say =E2=80=9Clook, sorry, we made a mistake, but the r=
ules are the rules and we can=E2=80=99t give you a AAA rating based on a mi=
stake.=E2=80=9D A credit rating is meant to reflect the credit quality of t=
he bonds, not the nuances of the relationship between the ratings agency an=
d the client. And yet!=C2=A0<em>You=C2=A0</em>try telling the client =E2=80=
