<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Carbon accounting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let us say, for simplicity, that you run a com=
pany that uses electric power, and you get half of your power from wind=C2=
=A0and half of your power from coal. The coal power you use puts one ton of=
 carbon dioxide into the atmosphere per year. The wind power you use puts z=
ero tons of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere;=C2=A0it is completely clean=
. The question is: How much total carbon emissions are you responsible for?=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might say: Well, one ton of carbon from th=
e coal, plus zero tons from the wind, equals one ton. But we <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29776711.281548/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTUvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1=
tb25leS1zdHVmZi1iaW5hbmNlLWZ0eC1hbmQtY2Fycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTIyMjJfTU9ORVlTVF=
VGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExM=
jImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7dba3249" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  talked the other day</a> about the financial services specialty of ESG=
 Consultant But Evil, where you advise companies on how to reduce their =E2=
=80=9Ccarbon emissions=E2=80=9D (a matter of accounting convention)=C2=A0wi=
thout actually reducing their <em>carbon emissions=C2=A0</em>(a matter of a=
ctual physical emissions into the atmosphere). And=C2=A0<em>as an accountin=
g convention</em>, you can improve on this math. Here is some better math:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your coal power adds one ton of carbo=
n to the atmosphere.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your wind pow=
er=C2=A0<em>subtracts=C2=A0</em>one ton of carbon from the atmosphere, beca=
use if you weren=E2=80=99t using the wind power you=E2=80=99d be using coal=
, which would add one ton of carbon emissions, and you=E2=80=99re not doing=
 that. So you can count the ton of carbon that you=E2=80=99re=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>using as a=C2=A0<em>reduction=C2=A0</em>of emissions.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So your net carbon emissions are zero.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I swear this is a real thing, or almost. Here=
=E2=80=99s a Bloomberg article titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29776711.281548/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9ncmFwaGljcy8yMDIyLWNhcmJvbi1vZmZzZXRzLXJlbmV3YWJsZS1lbmVyZ3kvP2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDExMjIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBa19457e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Junk Carbon Offsets Are What Make These Big Comp=
anies =E2=80=98Carbon Neutral=E2=80=99</a>=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Airlines, online retailers, industrial firms a=
nd energy producers now rely heavily on the cheapest and most suspect type =
of offset =E2=80=94 those tied to renewable-energy projects.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most of these renewable-energy offset purchase=
s are not credible, according to Julio Friedmann, chief scientist at consul=
tancy Carbon Direct and one of six researchers who reviewed the data. =E2=
=80=9CI would consider these to be low-quality credits that did not avoid o=
r reduce greenhouse-gas emissions,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purchasing credits tied to support of solar or=
 wind projects sounds good for the climate. But experts consider these offs=
ets largely bogus. The issue is timing: many renewable offsets came into be=
ing just as solar and wind power established themselves as the cheapest sou=
rce of energy in most countries. Selling offsets for small sums as a way to=
 support the economics of renewables doesn=E2=80=99t provide any real benef=
it if it=E2=80=99s already cheaper than building new coal or gas power plan=
ts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s the basis on which these offset=
s are generated: additional support for something clean is assumed to displ=
ace a dirtier alternative. Offsets built on firmer footing =E2=80=94 and co=
sting far more money =E2=80=94 now exist from a nascent industry that direc=
tly removes carbon dioxide from the air.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea is that if you support a renewable pr=
oject =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance by committing in advance to pay for some =
power produced by a proposed renewable project, so that it can get financin=
g to get built =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you are reducing emissions and should be=
 rewarded. But that can end up looking a lot like double-counting, where yo=
ur use of renewables doesn=E2=80=99t add to your emissions but also, someho=
w, subtracts from them.</p>
