 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> man</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The wipeout of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s cry=
pto empire, including its crown jewel FTX exchange and sister trading desk =
Alameda Research, is helping to reduce liquidity across the crypto market.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decline has been dubbed the =E2=80=9CAlame=
da Gap=E2=80=9D by blockchain-data firm Kaiko, named for the trading group =
at the center of the storm which is closing its books. Plunges in liquidity=
 usually come during periods of volatility as trading shops pull bids and a=
sks from their order books to better regulate risks, Kaiko noted in a Nov. =
17 newsletter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe Alameda Gap in liquidity could be=
 here to stay, at least in the short term,=E2=80=9D wrote the analysts. =C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These market makers fulfill an especially valu=
able role in the liquidity-sensitive crypto space by buying and selling coi=
ns. But as they turn more conservative in times of crisis, that results in =
thinner liquidity where users have greater difficulty buying or selling an =
asset, which in turn makes the market more volatile, said Hank Huang, chief=
 technology officer at Kronos Research.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMarket makers are shutting off or get=
ting funds into a safe place first,=E2=80=9D added Tiantian Kullander, co-f=
ounder of Singapore-based crypto trading platform Amber Group, adding that =
they=E2=80=99re =E2=80=9Cawaiting the storm to pass.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/29776711.281548/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvVHJl=
eW5vcl9kZWFsZXJfbW9kZWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcc8a1e79" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> simple =
model</a> of market making is that you buy a bunch of a thing as the price =
goes down and sell it as the price goes up; if the price is volatile but mo=
re or less mean-reverting then you make a lot of money buying low and selli=
ng high. If you buy a bunch as it goes down and then it goes down more and =
you buy more and it goes down more and you buy more and it goes down more a=
nd you buy more and it goes to zero and you have all of it, then that=E2=80=
=99s bad, for you. But you have provided a valuable service, to your custom=
ers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One simple (but speculative) model of how Alam=
eda blew up is that it might have provided that valuable service during the=
 blowup of the Luna token.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If you are a market maker in crypto in November 2022, you might l=
ook at that example and say, you know what, I=E2=80=99m going to take the r=
est of the year off, spend some quality time with my family, try not to cat=
ch any falling knives for a bit.</p>
